.TH HSH 1 "April 2026" "1.0" "Simple Shell Manual"

.SH NAME
hsh \- simple UNIX command line interpreter

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
.br
[ \fBcommand_string\fR | ] \fBhsh\fR

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX command-line interpreter that reads commands from standard input and executes them. It operates in both interactive and non-interactive modes, making it suitable for direct user interaction or piped command sequences.

.SH USAGE

.SS Interactive Mode
In interactive mode,
.B hsh
displays a prompt ("$ ") and waits for the user to type a command. After executing the command, the prompt is displayed again.

The user can exit the shell cleanly by typing the built-in command \fBexit\fR or by pressing \fBCtrl+D\fR (End Of File).

.SS Non-Interactive Mode
In non-interactive mode,
.B hsh
reads commands from standard input (via pipe or redirection), executes them sequentially, and exits automatically when the End Of File is reached.

.SH COMMAND EXECUTION

.B hsh
executes commands in the following order:

.IP 1.
Checks if the command is a built-in (exit, env).

.IP 2. 
If not a built-in, searches for the command:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2.1
If the command contains a '/' (absolute or relative path), it uses it directly.

.IP \(bu 2.2
Otherwise, it searches for the command in the directories listed in the PATH environment variable.
.RE
.IP 3.
If found, executes the command in an isolated child process using fork() and execve().

.IP 4.
Waits for the command to complete and retrieves its exit status before returning to the prompt.

.SH BUILT-IN COMMANDS

.TP
.B exit
Exits the shell. If no arguments are provided, it terminates using the exit status of the last executed command.
.TP

.B env
Prints all environment variables currently accessible to the shell.

.SH ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
.TP
.B PATH
List of directories to search for executable commands, separated by colons (:).
.TP

.B PWD
The current working directory (inherited from the parent process, not dynamically updated in v1).

.SH EXIT STATUS
.B hsh
returns the exit status of the last executed command. 
.br
If no command was executed, it exits with status 0. If a command is not found, the shell propagates an error status (typically 127, or 1 depending on internal handling).

.SH ERROR MESSAGES
When a command is not found/executable for any reason 
  (inexistant, not accessible, not an executable),
.B hsh
prints an error message to stderr in the following format:
.PP
.I ./hsh: 1: command: not found
.PP
Where
.I ./hsh
is the name of the shell (extracted from argv[0]),
.I 1
is the nth non-empty line read and
.I command
is the name of the command that failed to resolve.

.SH EXAMPLES

.SS Interactive Mode
.nf
$ ./hsh

$ ls -l

total 100
-rw-r--r-- 1 user user 1234 Apr 19 10:00 main.c

$ pwd

/home/user/simple_shell

$ exit
.fi


.SS Non-Interactive Mode
.nf
$ echo "ls" | ./hsh

main.c shell.c hsh

$ echo -e "pwd\\nls\\nexit" | ./hsh

/home/user/simple_shell

main.c shell.c hsh
.fi

.SH BUGS
No memory leaks known (verified via Valgrind).

.PP
As this is a v1 pedagogical project, the following standard shell features are strictly NOT implemented by design:

.IP "1." 3
Command separators (;, &&, ||)

.IP "2." 3
Pipes (|) between internal commands

.IP "3." 3
Redirections (>, <, >>)

.IP "4." 3
Globbing and Wildcards (*, ?)

.IP "5." 3
Variable expansion ($VAR)

.IP "6." 3
Quotes handling for arguments with spaces

.IP "7." 3
Comments (#)

.IP "8." 3
Directory navigation (cd)

